esents a new synthesis that breaks through essentialist stereotypes and contends that literature, like religion, points to an ineffable transcendental, to something beyond what we can adequately explain, prove, systematize, quantify, or enclose in a theory.Uttering the Unutterable explores how Aristotelian philosophy provides the most complete and compelling account of literature for philosophers, literary critics, and theorists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCriticism. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aReadingxPhilosophy. 0aReligion and literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAquinas.  aArnold.  aBabbitt.  aBarthes.  aBaudrillard.  aBernard Suits.  aChicago School.  aCuller.  aDerrida.  aDiogenes Laertius.  aEagleton.  aFish.  aFoucault.  aGod.  aJohn Gardner.  aKant.  aNicomachean Ethics.  aOccams razor.  aPlato.  aPocklington.  aPoetics.  aPresocratics.  aSaussure.  aSchmitt.  aSocrates.  aSydney.  aTupper.  aWinters.  aWittgenstein.  acriticism.  adeath of the author.  adivine.  aessentialism.  afamily resemblance.  afinal cause.  aformalism.  afour causes.  agenius.  ainspiration.  aliterary theory.  amaterialism.  ametaphor.  apoetry.  apost-modern.  areader response.  arealism.  astructuralism.  atelos.  atheoria.  atranscendence.  awonder.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228015222?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228015222423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228015222/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles